{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476546"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:49:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:49:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13780"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13780"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.02,0.03,0.16,0.65]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6399"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55950"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6399"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13780"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41499"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1328"},{"type":"tags","id":"1853"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11631"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12544"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42930"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44179"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55950"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn eight-year-old boy presents to his General Practice clinic with his parents. He has recently been diagnosed with Duchenne muscular dystrophy. He has no other significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits: pulse rate 88/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Cardiac examination is normal. An electrocardiogram (ECG), echocardiogram, and 24-hour Holter monitor are all normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cardiac complications is this child most likely to develop?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mitral valve prolapse","Supraventricular arrhythmias","Ventricular arrhythmias","Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy","Dilated cardiomyopathy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDilated cardiomyopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cardiac complication of Duchenne muscular dystrophy (DMD), occurring in up to 90% of patients over 18 years old. It is characterised by left ventricular dilation and systolic dysfunction. Onset is typically in the teenage years but can occur earlier.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn DMD, the absence of dystrophin in cardiac muscle leads to progressive fibrosis and replacement of myocardium with connective tissue and fat. This results in ventricular wall thinning and dilation. Early signs may include subtle ECG changes such as tall R waves in V1, deep Q waves in lateral leads, or sinus tachycardia. As the disease progresses, patients may develop symptoms of heart failure, including fatigue, dyspnea, and peripheral edema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERegular cardiac screening, including annual ECG and echocardiogram from the time of diagnosis, is crucial for early detection and management. Treatment typically involves ACE inhibitors or angiotensin receptor blockers, which may be started even before overt cardiac dysfunction is evident. Beta-blockers and diuretics may be added as the disease progresses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertrophic cardiomyopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is not a typical feature of Duchenne muscular dystrophy. It is more commonly associated with other neuromuscular disorders such as Friedreich ataxia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitral valve prolapse\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in Duchenne muscular dystrophy but is much less common than dilated cardiomyopathy. It is thought to be related to papillary muscle dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECardiac arrhythmias, both \u003Cstrong\u003Esupraventricular\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eventricular\u003C/strong\u003E, can occur in Duchenne muscular dystrophy. However, they are less common than dilated cardiomyopathy and typically occur later in the disease course, often secondary to advanced cardiomyopathy. When present, they may manifest as palpitations, syncope, or sudden cardiac death.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Dilated cardiomyopathy is the most common cardiac complication of Duchenne muscular dystrophy.","Regular cardiac screening is essential in Duchenne muscular dystrophy patients, even when asymptomatic."],"references":["Kang PB, Morrison L. Duchenne and Becker muscular dystrophy: Management and prognosis. In: UpToDate [online]; 2023 [updated 2023 Jan 6; cited 2024 Jun 19]. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/duchenne-and-becker-muscular-dystrophy-management-and-prognosis","Johnson R, Otway R, Chin E, Horvat C, Ohanian M, Wilcox JAL, et al. DMD-Associated Dilated Cardiomyopathy: Genotypes, Phenotypes, and Phenocopies. Circ Genom Precis Med. 2023 Oct;16(5):421-430. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37671549/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41499"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13780"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41499"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-